luation, setting up a critical execution-versus-confidence debate.\n\n## What the Model Says for VZ Stock\n\nWe assessed Verizon stock using assumptions tied to fiber expansion, subscriber recovery, and stable cash generation across a mature U.S. telecom base.\n\nBased on 2.3% revenue growth, 24.1% operating margins, and an 8.6x exit multiple, the model implies steady capital returns without valuation expansion. [...] That framework points to VZ stock reaching $60 per share, delivering 35% total upside and an 11% annualized return.\n\nverizon stock\n\nVZ Valuation Model Results (TIKR)\n\nStress-test VZ stocks earnings under slower wireless pricing and higher promotional intensity using TIKR for free →\n\nOur Valuation Assumptions\n\nTIKR’s Valuation Model lets you plug in your own assumptions for a company’s revenue growth, operating margins, and P/E multiple, and calculates the stock’s expected returns.\n\nHere’s what we used for VZ stock:\n\n### 1. Revenue Growth: 2.3%\n\nVerizon Communications Inc. generated $138 billion in LTM revenue, with growth averaging 1% to 3% over five years across a saturated U.S. wireless market.', 'score': 0.9985335, 'raw_content': None}, {'url': 'https://finance.yahoo.com/markets/stocks/articles/verizon-communications-stock-soaring-2026-212000110.html', 'title': "Verizon Communications Stock Is Soaring in 2026. Here's ...", 'content': 'It finished 2025 with a modest 2.5% increase in revenue, with its top line climbing to $138.2 billion. Its operating income of $29.3 billion also rose by a modest 2%. While those weren\'t necessarily blowout numbers for the business, they did energize investors and give them confidence that the business is moving in the right direction under new CEO Dan Schulman, who said, "Verizon will no longer be a hunting ground \u200dfor our competitors." The company also unveiled a strong forecast for profit and cash flow for the year ahead that beat analysts\' expectations.\n\n## Why Verizon\'s stock looks destin